text: Regioselective 1,2-addition of organometallic reagents to unprotected juglones Kathlyn A. Parker a,⇑ Article history: Received 11 December 2014 Accepted 17 December 2014 Available online 26 December 2014 Keywords: Juglone 1,2-Addition Stereoselectivity Quinols Quinols are important synthetic precursors, pharmaceuticals, metabolic and biosynthetic intermediates, and chemical photore- sists.1 The most direct access to this class of molecules is the 1,2- addition of an organometallic reagent to a quinone. Grignard and alkyllithium reagents have been used most frequently for this pur- pose and, more recently, organocadmium reagents have been employed.2 Despite the potential of this approach to quinols, its utility may be complicated by the formation of double 1,2-addition products and/or Michael addition products,3,4 as well as hydroquinones (via electron-transfer processes).5 Although differentiation of the carbonyls in unsymmetrical quinones by electronic and/or steric effects can lead to the formation of a single quinol,2,6,7 addition to these systems generally yields mixtures of regioisomers. Herein we report that treatment of juglone (1a) or 2-bromojug- lone (1b) with one equivalent of an alkyllithium or Grignard reagent yields a monoadduct in which 1,2-addition has taken place at the C-1 carbonyl. Our experiments indicate that the hydrogen- bonded juglone hydroxyl groups are not deprotonated in these reactions. This surprising, regioselective reaction gives quinol adducts cleanly and in good yield. Contents lists available at ScienceDirect Tetrahedron Letters 56 (2015) 3500–3502 products,8 we are interested in the regioselective addition of nucle- ophiles to unsymmetrical quinones. Of particular interest for our plans are the monoadducts of 5-hydroxy or 5-alkoxy naphthoqui- nones. Although the literature describes the addition of aryllithium and Grignard reagents to 1-hydroxyanthraquinones,9 similar additions to juglones have not been reported.10 We view adducts in the juglone series as key intermediates in syntheses of complex aryl C-glycosides such as the gilvocarcins,11 pluramycins,12 and griseusins.13

Slow addition of a solution of methyllithium to juglone (1a) in THF at (cid:2)78 (cid:3)C led to the observation (tlc) that complete reaction had occurred after the transfer of only 1.2 equiv of the organome- tallic reagent (Scheme 1). The structure of the product, obtained in good yield as a single isomer, was assigned as 2a4 on the basis of the presence of a strongly hydrogen-bonded phenolic proton in the NMR spectrum.14 Similarly, addition of (12.26 ppm) 1.2 equiv of methyllithium to 2-bromo juglone (1b, prepared by the scheme of Jung and Hagenah)15 afforded quinol 2b and addi- tion of n-butyllithium gave quinol 2c (Table 1). In each of these cases, the yield of monoadduct was good and regiochemistry was conﬁrmed by a nuclear Overhauser effect (NOE) NMR experiment (see Supplementary material). Indeed, if the hydroxyl group is present during the addition step, it must be involved in differentiating the two carbonyl groups. Not surprisingly, the strong intramolecular hydrogen bonding of juglone has not gone unrecognized and is the subject of a num- ber of spectroscopic investigations.17 Also, its effect as a director of reactions has been elegantly regiochemistry in Diels Alder applied.18

To test the hypothesis that regiochemistry of addition is con- trolled by the involvement of the hydrogen-bonding hydroxyl group, we prepared the sodium alkoxides of both juglone and 2- bromojuglone (treatment with sodium hydride in reﬂuxing t-butyl methyl ether; complete deprotonation indicated by the volume of H2 captured) and subjected each to the addition of methyllithium. In each case, we obtained a mixture of products. Likewise, subjec- tion of the methyl ether of either juglone or 2-bromojuglone19 to the reaction conditions led to the production of a mixture of compounds. Although MeLi and nBuLi yielded clean 1,2 addition adducts, addition of sBuLi, tBuLi, or PhLi20 to juglone under similar condi- tions gave complex product mixtures. Presumably the rate of pro- ton abstraction is faster with these more basic reagents and the resulting alkoxide undergoes addition without regioselectivity. On the other hand, both methylmagnesium bromide and vinyl- magnesium bromide added to juglone cleanly to give quinols 2a and 2d, respectively, in good yields. Treatment of juglone with AlMe3, ZnEt2, or lithium dimethylcuprate resulted only in the recovery of starting material. The regioselective addition of organometallics to unprotected juglones is likely to be the method of choice for the preparation of the densely functionalized 4,8-dihydroxy-1(4H)-naphthalenone nucleus. The organometallic reagent (0.12 mmol; solution in ether or THF as provided) was added drop- wise. After stirring for 30 min, the reaction mixture was quenched by addition of water (1 mL) and warmed to rt. The mixture was diluted with ether (30 mL) and washed with brine (3 (cid:3) 20 mL). The combined aqueous solution was extracted with ether (2 (cid:3) 10 mL). The organic extracts were combined and the resulting solution was dried over MgSO4 and concentrated under reduced pressure. The crude product was puriﬁed by ﬂash chromatography on silica gel with mixtures of ethyl acetate/hexane.

General procedure for the deprotonation of juglones and addition (1b) organometallics: of (0.10 mmol) was dissolved in t-butyl methyl ether (10 mL) and NaH (3 mg, 0.125 mmol) was added. The resulting mixture was stirred at reﬂux (1–2 h) until the volume of H2 (captured in a water-ﬁlled graduated cylinder placed up-side-down in a beaker of water; the graduated cylinder was connected to the reaction ﬂask via tubing containing a drying tube ﬁlled with CaSO4) indi- cated complete deprotonation of the substrates (volume of H2: ca. 2 mL).
